questionRound.0.question.11.answer: I did a double look-ahead of sorts: | 1) Note the higher average payoff choice in my table. | 2) Note the higher average payoff choice in the table of whom I depend on. | 3) Note the higher average payoff choice of whom he/she depends on. | 4) Check if that gives the middle man the best payoff  if it's a terrible payoff  then switch middle man's intention. | 5) Switch my intention if new middle man intention gives low payoff for me.

If i am red on display 3  I will look at the four payoffs in the boxes and see which one is the highest. Then I will look at the four payoffs on the next box and see what Green might choose. If necessary I will also look at the four payoffs on the third box to help me think what Blue might choose and that might affect Green's choice. At the end  if I think Green decides to choose XG  then I will pick the higher one from XR XG and YR YG.

I noticedthat there is always one person with a clear choice of which to choose after I was that person one trial early on.  For  that person  they should always choose one option over the other regardless of how the group plays. I then worked backwards  assuming others had discovered this strategy to see what choice would be best for each person including the one who dictated my outcome. When I knew what their best outcome would be  I knew how to choose to maximize my own reward. The most frustating thing waas when the person before me acted illogically and made the wrong decision but I knew it was a different player every time and continued to play as if others also discovered how to get the most out of the game.

I think everyone is ultimately interested in gaining the most. The only person with an obvious strategy is purple  because he has a guaranteed higher gain if he chooes XP. If from there everyone assumes purple will choose XP  Maroon should choose YM so they get the higher of the XP pairings  likewise  Organge will choose YO assuming Maroon chooses YM  and if the pattern continues  I choose the higher of the two "high" numbers.

In the beginning  I chose what would get me the most tokens  without taking into account the decision on whom my payoff rested (Person A).  After a while  I took their decision on what would get them the most tokens into consideration  before looking at the third person (Person B) in the chain: If Person B chose X  then Person A would probably choose Y  so I should choose Y  and so on.

One color always had an easy choice to make  usually the one on the farthest right hand side. After figuring out which choice that color would make  one could work backwards and figure out the logical decision everyone else would make. This usually worked out.

Find the color with the highest values both in one row. That is the one they will choose. Assume all others will see this and make a choice based on the fact that this person is in control and will decide based on choosing the one that will get them the most coins realistically. follow that line all the way until you get to your color and choose X or Y based on how many coins you could actually get.

Purple always has an option that is guaranteed to make more money than the other option  regardless of what the color before them chooses. As such  it is in their best interest to choose that one (Xp). From that  I see what the most profitable option for the other colors will be  and therefore the most probably option that they are going to choose  based on what Purple chooses since purple is almost guaranteed to choose Xp. I make my decision based off of that.
Tried to predict which decisions the color after me would make  so I could match that for the biggest payoff.

I attempted to guess what the players in front of me would choose based on their perception of choices of the players in front of them. Sometimes it worked  but I think one or two players based their decisions on luck or did not fully predict the movements of others  which ruined my plan...

I looked for the two highest numbers in my payoff box. Then I looked at the highest number in the payoff box of the color that will effect my payoff. If their highest payoff is X  I will go to my X options and see which one has the higher number. It most often happened to be the two highest numbers in the box. If not  then I picked the option that had the highest  | number.

I just find a role that the smaller one of the X or Y is larger or equivalent to the larger one of another. So people shall choose the larger one  then deductive and think about which everyone will choose using the numbers in the form  then choose the best answer. Maybe sometimes the strategy will fail due to some reasons of chance  but most of time this strategy is feasible since everyone will choose the larger one for more token  and your result is directly influenced by their choices.
